info","should_display_ad_info":false},"serialized_frtp_identifiers":null,"debug_info":null,"inform_treatment_for_community_notes":null,"message":{"text":"As a wedding planner, one of the most critical steps in ensuring a smooth, seamless event is conducting a venue visit prior to the big day. While photos and floorplans are helpful, there is no substitute for walking the space in person. Here\u2019s why it\u2019s a must:\n\n1. Logistical Planning & Layout Accuracy\n\nSeeing the venue in person allows us to take exact measurements, assess traffic flow, and visualize the layout. We can determine the best placement for the ceremony, cocktail hour, reception tables, DJ, photo booth, and more. It also helps avoid any surprises, like low ceilings where a tall floral arch won\u2019t fit or uneven flooring that could be a tripping hazard.\n\n2. Identifying Venue Restrictions & Power Sources\n\nMany venues have specific rules\u2014like no open flames, early end times, or sound ordinances\u2014that aren\u2019t always obvious until you visit and speak to the onsite coordinator. A walkthrough also helps locate power outlets for lighting, entertainment, and catering, ensuring your vendors are fully prepared.\n\n3. Confirming Guest Experience & Flow\n\nA venue visit gives us the chance to walk the event as a guest would. Where do they park? How far is the walk to the ceremony space? Are there accessibility concerns? We want to ensure a smooth experience for everyone, from the grandparents to the bridal party.\n\nIn short, a venue visit allows your planner to anticipate problems before they happen and bring your vision to life with confidence and precision. It\u2019s a behind-the-scenes step that makes a big difference in your event\u2019s
